<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>House of Commons Select Committee on Environment Food &amp; Rural Affairs</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Submission from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Prof Tim Benton, University of Leeds</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK’s food security can be improved by (a) increasing productivity and its resilience locally, (b) increasing the resilience of the international food supply chain, accounting for 40-50% of our food use, (c) reducing waste of food already grown/imported, (d) helping people manage diets and dietary choices better, and reducing over-consumption.  Arguably, greater impacts on local food security will arise from (b-d) than from increasing productivity locally.  Ensuring both sustainability and resilience are key issues, even if they “cost” in yield terms.  Taking a food systems view is crucial in planning for a world made more variable by climate and where food and other resources are increasingly competed for.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Introductory comment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am an academic and also the “Champion” of the UK’s Global Food Security (GFS) programme</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which is a partnership of the main public funders of research in disciplines relating to the provision and use of food.  The role of GFS is to help coordinate research in this area and act as a conduit between research and stakeholders.  The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs is a partner within GFS.  The views expressed are not those of the GFS partnership but my own, as an academic expert in food security. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the paragraphs below, I address the questions as posed by the Call for Evidence.  Throughout, I refer to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">food security</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as when everyone has continual access to sufficient, safe, affordable and nutritious food, sustainably produced.  The WHO definition, on which this is based, uses the term “all people, at all times” which implies sustainability by including future generations. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">sensu stricto</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, is about the ability to continue production into the future, but also encompasses the desire not to change things, e.g. via biodiversity loss, in such a way as to reduce future generation’s choices.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Resilience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> refers to the ability of a system to withstand perturbations</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Sustainability and resilience are thus related concepts: in a variable world, sustainable systems are by definition resilient to change.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There has been significant discussion about food retailers cutting margins to levels that are economically unsustainable.  This is often framed in terms of the difference between farm incomes and the direct costs of production.  However, I wish to focus on the impact of “squeezed margins” on the environmental sustainability of the food supply.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is well recognised in both the scientific and grey literature that environmental and ecological processes provide “ecosystem services” that support the production of food</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  These ecosystem services include processes that generate and maintain soil fertility, pollination, natural pest control and so on.  Production is also enhanced by equitable climate and water availability.  Agriculture can also reduce non-production ecosystem services that have value for others.  This includes impacting on water quality, water quantity, biodiversity and the cultural value of the landscape.  These “downstream impacts” can be considerable, the European Nitrogen Assessment in 2011</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> estimated the costs of using nitrogen fertiliser on human health (via air quality impacts), on terrestrial, aquatic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and marine biodiversity (including impacts on marine fisheries via impacting on water quality) exceeded the economic benefits of boosting yields.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As an approximation, increasing sustainability, beyond a narrow framing of increasing efficiency, will always cost in terms of production foregone</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – via setting aside land to provide services (buffer strips, habitat for pollinators), or using less, or lower-impacting, inputs.  Unsustainable practices are also cumulative in their impacts in the long term.  Soils can be “mined” for their nutrients for some years before yields are significantly reduced</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and erosion can occur at a significant rate but one that takes decades to deplete resources to the point of losing functionality (a recent Swiss</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> study indicated losses of 0.75 tonnes per hectare per year).  Habitat can be lost and degraded incrementally from areas before populations – whether pollinators, natural enemies, weeds, birds or mammals - pass an “extinction threshold” and are lost locally.  Many leading environmental scientists, including myself, recognise that recent practices have been unsustainable and that future production would be jeopardised if significantly greater efforts were not made towards sustainability.  Sustainable intensification requires a significant reshaping of agricultural practices.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given that margins are squeezed throughout the supply chain, producers often do not invest in sustainability to the extent required for the long-term.  Analysis of food prices by the NGO TruCost</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for waste, water, carbon and “pollution” costs, indicated that 6-18% of the purchase price would be needed to offset the externalisation of the costs of production.  This implies that improving the sustainability of production, via replacing the natural capital “spent on production” requires an increase in food prices, and for this premium to flow to farmers to invest in sustainability.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food security;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK food security requires citizens being able to afford a safe and nutritious diet that is produced sustainably.  In the UK, obesity is increasing which implies over-consumption of calories (a recent US study indicates that the observed patterns of weight-gain imply over-consumption in the order of 10-20% of the daily energy budget on average</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).  In addition, work by WRAP</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimates that across household, hospitality and food service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, manufacturing and retail there is around 12 million tonnes of food wasted, 75% of which could have been avoided – with a value of &gt;£19 billion. The ca 9 million tonnes if avoidable food waste is equivalent to ca 21% of all food purchased</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and over-consumptive diseases (~£16 bn in 2007; Public Health England), it suggests that eating wisely and reducing waste could cut the UK’s demand for food by perhaps as much as one third.  Clearly, this wou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ld contribute to food security via reducing the absolute demand to produce or import food.  This could be positive for the UK economy and revenue-neutral for consumers and retailers: within the same household spend on food, reducing waste and eating according to nutrition-guideline amounts would free up a portion of the budget that could be invested in trading-up the food’s nutritional and environmental values.  WRAP econometric analysis suggests that about half of the money saved from reducing waste was invested in trading-up to better quality food.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Volatility is increasing in three main interacting areas: production, pricing and demand.  Globally, what was historically extreme weather is now becoming significantly common, which is impacting on supply volatility</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Pricing – and how it reacts to changes in supply and demand - has been affected by increasing speculative investments in the food supply chain </span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Growth in global demand for food </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is outstripping supply growth leading to upward pressures on food prices, and increasing competition for food.  These factors interact to amplify weather-driven variations in supply into price volatility.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Volatility in global supply chains implies that, for some goods, at some times, access to supplies at an affordable price will be constrained.  The retail chain is generally aware of this and is expending considerable effort in ensuring their supply chains are resilient.  However, the UK remains at risk.  For example, soy is integral to the food chain (a high percentage of processed foods contain soy) and it is also an important source of protein in livestock feed.  Soy is produced in South America and the US and increasingly is demanded by Asian consumers.  For example, China’s demand for imported soy is growing rapidly: S American- China soy trade is the largest commodity trade flow in the world (~60MT imported from A America in 2012, demand is 15% higher this year, owing to poor Chinese harvests</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).  The EU is the second major user of soy and is increasingly competing with China for access to soy.  Were the Chinese harvest (it is the world’s 4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> largest producer) to fail, what would be the impact on UK accessibility to soy and what would be the impact on protein availability in food and feed?</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Inevitably, such a supply squeeze would significantly increase prices for food and feed (and lead to significant economic impacts on the meat and dairy sector).  Price fluctuations will likely have the biggest impact on the poorest.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Analysis of purchases following the 2007/8 food price spike</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> show a complex pattern of changes in response to food price increases: as prices increased UK households bought 4.2% less.  They also traded down to save money, by buying cheaper alternatives.  Nonetheless, trading down didn’t compensate prices rises and overall the food bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for an average family </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rose and was 12% more in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2011 than 2007.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The poorest spent 17% more in 2011 compared to 2007, so their relative food bill increased by 40% more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than average.  Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">obesogenicity of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">diets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tends to increase with poverty</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The growth of reliance on foodbanks, with the Trussel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Trust estimating close to 350000 people relied on donated food in 2012-13, suggests that food poverty (i.e. food insecurity) is a major and growing factor within the UK.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK food security can be improved by using resources more efficiently, and this includes food already produced: minimising waste, especially in the home, and help people make food choices that are not over-consumptive.  Labelling and storage guidelines, and public health messaging are important in this regard.  Analysis by WRAP indicates that the UK household food waste is equivalent to the production from approx. 91% of  the land area of Wales</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Thus, reducing this demand side pressure is equivalent to freeing up land.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Using resources, including land, more efficiently could also grow UK production.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">My view is that it is possible to optimise land-use in the UK to encourage production growth in those areas most suited, and where the environmental costs are most limited.  Some of this thinking is reflected in the Green Food Project’s synthesis report.  However, there are important evidence needs to underpin “smart land use for multifunctional landscapes”</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As Spratt (2013)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> indicates, reducing speculation on the food markets can potentially have significant benefits whilst having minor costs, notably in curtailing the profit-making potential of a small number of financial institutions.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Similarly, it is possible to imagine a variety of financial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">instruments that lead to virtual commodity stores, such as a “dynamic biofuel mandate” that diverts grain-for-biofuel into food when prices rise</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given fluctuations in supply, demand and prices, as well as the increasing potential for competition for resources, such as land and water, to drive civil and international conflicts, some greater thought should be given to having a “Plan B” for if/when the functionality of the global market breaks down.  For example, in a well-functioning and non-fluctuating market, it makes sense to produce those goods where we have a comparative advantage, exporting the excess and importing things we don’t produce.  However, in times of perturbation, such a strategy doesn’t work.  Thanet Earth</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the large greenhouse complex in Kent, is an interesting case study which indicates the potential to diversify production in a viable way and reduce our reliance on imports.  Incentivising relatively small land areas, given to modern, efficient, under-glass horticulture could produce a significant amount of UK demands.  Incentivising production of a range of products may increase our resilience to future supply problems.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In a world where extreme weather is becoming appreciably common, farmers growing fewer products risk “putting all their eggs in one basket”.  Recent research</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> indicates that farmers growing a greater diversity of products spread their risks and reduce income variance (albeit at some cost to overall income; although that can, potentially, be offset by better forecasting and playing the markets).  Diversified landscapes are also likely to be better at delivering a range of ecosystem services</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> , and managing waste via promoting more “circular thinking”, and thus are likely to be both economically resilient and more sustainable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning; </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Climate risks are inherently uncertain as they depend on the future emissions pathway and the eventuating climate impacts.  The impact of extreme weather on food production is increasing; but its future impact is, by its nature, very difficult to predict.  Understanding how weather will change is an area of considerable research endeavour, but 10 year probabilistic weather forecasting is unlikely to be useful for some years to come yet.  In the meantime, we ought to both plan for the likely weather (based on climate change projections) and unlikely but high-impact events.  In a previous report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the need for “realistic worst case scenarios” to be developed for planning to ensure UK food systems’ resilience was highlighted. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One area of planning is to better understand the potential role of UK agriculture in exporting onto the global market.  As indicated by the growing literature on global impacts of climate on agricultural production</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the 5 major calorie-producing parts of the world (the mid West, the Latin American soy belt, NW Europe, the Indo-Ganges and SE Asia, and China), NW Europe is projected to suffer least in yield terms.  This means our “comparative advantage” in production will increase, leading to ever greater economic potential to export.  How will this impact on our food security, land use and environmental sustainability?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ways of increasing self-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK should not aim for self-sufficiency in a world of global markets, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where &gt; 60% of all agricultural production is traded internationally</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Greater self-sufficiency implies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">diversifying production</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inevitably leads to producing things where we have less comparative ad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vantage.  As outlined in paras 14 and 15</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, however, some diversification is a useful bet-hedge against weather impacts and market failures.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Self-sufficiency implies a market preference for locally produced goods rather than imported ones.  There is certainly growth in consumer desire for locally produced goods, perhaps because it inspires greater trust and implies shorter supply chains.  However, sometimes the economic gains of exporting “high quality produce” vs importing “low quality produce” (a prime example is in pork, where we export about 183kT of pork and import about 729kT, essentially replacing “premium” for “value” products).  Clearly, greater self-sufficiency in pork is possible, but it would require changing access to imported meat.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security.</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">My own feeling is that, for the time being, increasing UK yields – via whatever means- will have a small impact on UK food security.  It may increase our economic security via feeding an export market; but reducing demand (para 7) will potentially do far more to freeing up food than producing a little more.  Our excellent genetics (plant and animal sciences) may play a greater role in enhancing global food security.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Non-genetic sciences potentially have a greater role in ensuring sustainability via maintaining ecosystem services and reducing competition for land and thus allowing multifunctional landscapes.  This includes remote sensing to map yield potential and habitat availability, the development of better precision agriculture, development of better agri-environment schemes and the understanding of how to manage the amount, quality and connectivity of non-cropped land, recycling technologies (from “field to flush”) to reduce waste and enhance sustainability and so on.  Sustainable intensification requires considerably more than animal and plant breeding.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> can contribute to increased resilience;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Resilient supply chains are ones that can function despite shocks.  Two notions of resilience apply here.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Risk-spreading</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> via ensuring supply chains have some redundancy (e.g. China imports soy from North and South America partly to reduce the risk of infrastructural failure of transport bottlenecks around S American ports).  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Risk reduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is about planning for the long term.  Retailers are increasingly building (a) longer-term relationships of trust with suppliers, ensuring that suppliers are environmentally and socially sustainable; (b) taking into account long-term risk in planning sourcing strategies, including looking ahead up to 20 years and assessing climate impacts.  The latter is, of course, hampered by uncertainty of knowledge as outlined in para 16 (climate).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase product</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ion and access new markets; </span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While the predominant business model is based on a “stack ‘em high, sell ‘em cheap” model, where there is significant market concentration in the major corporations and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> business models</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that lead to extreme pressure on margins</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, small produce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s, without the benefit of volume, will have problems competing.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Encouraging a greater public appreciation on values (quality, nutritional, environmental, para 7) rather than price would potentially improve market accessibility.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Likewise, some thinkers are imagining “a world without waste”</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Ensuring unavoidable waste and losses (food waste, food processing waste, farm waste, manure and sewerage) can be fully utilised (para 21) requires some new thinking (and research on) how best to utilise waste streams, including addressing regulatory burdens and difficulty in obtaining planning consents.  Inevitably, the more waste can be reduced (or reused), the more price rises could be buffered.  Managing inevitable waste as a resource is part of food security; and more could be done to enable and encourage this on-farm.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Concluding remarks</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Economic growth and ensuring a reliable and sustainable food supply are both important aims.  Encouraging healthy dietary choices and reducing waste – and thereby decreasing demand – has the potential to drive a “win-win-win” (health, environment, food security) solution.  This potentially allows producers to be paid more for producing less, but in a more environmentally sustainable way.  The UK has a strong potential to lead a “race to the top” to show that food systems for “sustainable nutrition” are both possible and profitable.  Thus, food security, for the UK (and globally) is not about producing more and more cheaply and accepting unsustainability: it is about encouraging respect for food, reducing waste, and managing production to protect the environment to allow our children and grandchildren to have the same securities we have now.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> See www.foodsecurity.ac.uk</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> CS Holling (1973) Resilience &amp; Stability of Ecological Systems Ann Rev Ecol Syst</span><span style="color:#666666; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 4: 1-23</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> UK NEA; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">E. Nelson</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic"> et al.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, Modeling multiple ecosystem services, biodiversity conservation, commodity production, and tradeoffs at landscape scales. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Front. Ecol. Environ.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, 4 (Feb, 2009); S. G. Potts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic"> et al.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, Global pollinator declines: trends, impacts and driv